Dear friends,

Just as many businesses are transforming to become more capable by using AI, universities are too. I recently visited the UK to receive an honorary doctorate from the University of Exeter’s Faculty of Environment, Science and Economy. The name of this faculty stood out to me as a particularly forward-looking way to organize an academic division. Having Computer Science sit alongside Environmental Science and the Business School creates natural opportunities for collaboration across these fields.

Leveraging AI leads a university to do things differently. Speaking with Vice Chancellor Lisa Roberts, Deputy Vice Chancellor Timothy Quine, and CS Department Head Andrew Howes, I was struck by the university leadership’s pragmatic and enthusiastic embrace of AI. This is not a group whose primary worry is whether students will cheat using AI. This is a group that is thinking about how to create a student body that is empowered through AI, whether by teaching more students to code, helping them use AI tools effectively, or showing them what’s newly possible in their disciplines.

Exeter is a wonderful place to create synergies between AI, environmental science, and business. It hosts 5 of the world’s top 21 most influential climate scientists (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KBn3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3kGW1sgcg97Rh-bzW94V67Z3HCXHyW8cKj7-254NP5W5cCfs62ZFRyKW5P3BXy1gP7MHW10dC4L1kBZSWW1yJtr-8mcP3MVH9Dk744W919W8RsD723zCgNfW1t0VnJ6g89k4W6Q4GYf5DC4rBW3N8Mzn8S3z_NW4KJ9vV67-9GvW3W3qDL8ltk4PW3g9Lmm4Y5ZX-V4489z8PW51BW84JS7X3B_rF1W4DR3fc6bM0xFVkG8FX5Wc_B7W1WQkxd4sN8BRW4rHP572Q_mk0W1_0cFv1-yJDyW5zNDms2278mQW4MMgwx7jnTDgW7RxgdX8N9trQVbS7th2dmj_nW6z7zf46XfqKCW5StQbp1XMB9TdtcMZ604 )  according to Reuters, and its scholars are major contributors to reports by the UN’s IPCC (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change) as well as pioneers in numerous areas of climate research including geoengineering, which I wrote (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KBn3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3mJV1-4Vz5mJxnGW3cbq425SZpWSW2QBFVV2QrJJQW3LpfDv6yTNdJW3xr4707Z-Lw7W4-3DFr9858cdVXnL4c53KwbqW5BNMNg40vGdFW6MdrnG2QgBFhW1ZwXgm4R9PJ4W4Yk84Q6QQspVW5J_T1M6FyGHJW62Q6VF4hvwpBW4_-63Y8cwTzHW8xqbHJ1B8jKvN7sTJmT1wWSxW4hyb_K7TzC8vW1ZrZ8R3BhSwQW1SHpBm9l954pW7mHgzJ6XHyZCW1PCXX07_sdVmW4HJtXr3CBwkhW4Wf_vg6D9B5QW8g0Cjh4QQGH6N5WGchBf7bKzW3sT7k12f40HLW472QM78s9NvfW8Cc6hH3P4kr6f84ST7q04 ) about previously. Its Centre for Environmental Intelligence, a partnership with the Met Office (the UK’s national weather service), applies AI to massive climate datasets. More work like this is needed to understand climate change and strategies for mitigation and adaptation. Add to this its Business School — named Business School of the Year (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KB43prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mDW570BVw6KvqvPW2PDNMd4JdLyBVStb5S89Wm8zVGK3-Q82SwlTN4gZ5m2bVtVyVjQL4H2qGyM1W1l4t1w7mtVtzN4jWDG08Rg_fW6SsbSG7wYzytN61j9nbmC7m0W46DGlj1NzdxtN2tDdN756_JRW76XyNR6vm2HdW8_JB0P18ShQhW5bBgcs2PskVCW1842mP7TTrHzW4Sr3C-7zRrzCW9fQXkT2wGHfPN8SZkKhGGHBDW49FsK43fk3B3W4DX6mR7nMkMgW1k3rh02JZRfqW4YKqPT4DqzZgN8k9MbcFkmhyN6ycwF_ZtJpvMH3Pp51kSr5f8yQwH404 ) by the consultancy Times Higher Education — and you have the ingredients for building applications and pursuing interdisciplinary studies that span technological, environmental, and economic realities.

Having been born in the UK and spent most of my career in Silicon Valley, I find it exciting to see Exeter’s leadership embrace AI with an enthusiasm I more often associate with California. The UK has always punched above its weight in research, and seeing that tradition continue in the AI era is encouraging.

Just as every company is becoming an AI company, every university must become an AI university — not just teaching AI, but using it to advance every field of study. This doesn’t mean abandoning disciplinary expertise. It means maintaining technical excellence while ensuring AI enhances every field.

Like almost all other universities and businesses worldwide, Exeter’s AI transformation is just beginning. But the enthusiastic embrace of AI by its leadership will give it momentum. As someone who is proud to be an honorary graduate of the university, I look forward to seeing what comes next!

Keep building,

Andrew

GPT-5 Takeoff Encounters Turbulence

OpenAI launched GPT-5, the highly anticipated successor to its groundbreaking series of large language models, but glitches in the rollout left many early users disappointed and frustrated.

What’s new: Rather than a family of models, GPT-5 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KzP3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3l_W76_pQB4HpL2nW4l9DTD1ltZMDW6SMHbT4N8gNBW7v31wj3NtB_zW9kLhlc1_qqtJW7jKSX96_dPqLVd0zZd71YP4fW4dJbgY5vM9-lW3-JXdy94PKfXW1l6Sf_6RXQ05W3YZCPq6rpWHlW3VHk0_6QPn1tW76YcQ17VXlcWW4qzHmK1pyRGKW4rWtBy6qJM8LW5x5DVb1slbj0W2JhlLH9hwq_KW3nG__X7JmLs9V2742j1sMM3kW3NwJTz5cy6ghW1Xc1ZC4Cy4NFW4Lg1701-6M4KW4C2WFv7LhTvwVzd99x5t4hxWf8DDJnR04 ) is a family of systems — GPT-5, GPT-5 Mini, GPT-5 Nano, and GPT-5 Pro — that include non-reasoning and variable-reasoning models along with a router that switches between them automatically depending on the input. - The router selects between non-reasoning and reasoning models based on input “type,” “complexity,” tool requirements, and explicit user intent (such as a prompt to “think hard”). The router learns from user behavior. When ChatGPT users reach usage limits, the router directs queries to mini versions of each model.
- The team trained the models on web content, licensed data, and human and generated input. They fine-tuned them to reason via reinforcement learning.
- In addition, they fine-tuned the models to prefer helpful but “safe” answers over refusals to answer, an approach the team calls safe completions. Given a potentially problematic input, a model aims to respond usefully while staying within safety guidelines, explains when it must refuse, and suggests related outputs that don’t touch on topics it has been trained to avoid.

Why it matters: OpenAI models have consistently topped language benchmarks. With GPT-5, the company has launched a system architecture that integrates its best models and takes advantage of the strengths of each: rapid output, slower output with adjustable computation devoted to reasoning, and graceful degradation to smaller versions.

We’re thinking: Novices may find that the GPT-5 router’s ability to choose a model for any given input simplifies things, but it remains to be seen whether expert users, who may be better at selecting the appropriate model for their tasks, will be happy to give up this control.

India Pushes to Build Indigenous AI

India, which has limited funding and large numbers of languages and dialects, is redoubling its efforts to build native large language models.

What’s new: India is funding startups and marshaling processing resources, MIT Technology Review reported (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KBH3prCCW95jsWP6lZ3kLW24PCXl9c-r_DN1GLR_FYD2msW3bQFsh8gZnbrW5fFj7-2LH85LW1fHXFz2H65F4N2dPXT8XwpflMCrb7ytH9vcW3Q3XL524YqhvW3P1jjD5dC3BHW3T-vZq6b482yW2tZWZg22jfgnW5zYFCJ6brB9FN88RWt1H4_nVW5NlLR225xSz0W1Pg30M5-3KXlW8DfGXR7wdCxqW1p2CjT57XqpFW5dscg93rgcHGN2lgyTM5gjxfW3kdHr-2qkJwDVc3BQm2p6NT6W1pM-4S7qXXLWW2gTkrS6nfMgtW4VTnCr9fg2m0W48jmYq1PlTBhW6sVy4Y19lb7kW63t7cc2NvW4dN2NbZfVTfMCDN6HTR_9nZdlcW5k9Bhk3TrLqkf1fLj9204 ) . Companies such as CoRover, Sarvam AI, and Soket AI Labs are working on efficient models that can process many of the 22 officially recognized languages spoken in India while running on relatively small compute budgets.

Challenges: India is home to more than 120 languages and 19,500 dialects. However, training models to process them faces hurdles both cultural and technical.

- Some Indian languages don’t have much written text or consistent spelling, which makes for few large, high-quality datasets for model training.
- Languages such as Hindi, Kannada and Tamil can be written without delimiters between words, such as spaces, which makes them difficult to tokenize efficiently.
- India lacks the financial muscle available in China, Europe, and the United States. Last year, the U.S. spent 3.5 percent of its gross domestic product on research and development, China spent 2.68 percent, and Europe spent 2.2 percent, while India spent 0.65 percent. The picture is more stark when it comes to funding startups. In 2024, U.S. AI startups amassed (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KyW5m_5PW5BWr2F6lZ3kvW1fyHhW5-wgSRV6XH2g2n-Z3lVXvQlN3rgxj-W6K-Z-96QLWS9W8M74WM52b_X9W4WYmt-6Xh7M1W31mVfb45PSJ0W312zCt378Bz9VRH63L1CQxQfW5jpHb662ZM8mW46lYqK8YMn2VW983mYT5400xDW6j-MLS3DRVnDW5zbQCJ13yDlJW59DX622PnHLkW3ngSV58KhxtLW27kjHP3LqpFPN5m0zKFHNTzDW3psG-G8PCn44W12fKr-8sq-XcW6Vjr5y1RY4vkVXQDgR6L6Fh-N3kgMFK7sx10W6TTNYG3bkRPXVmdSyH7K_KNSV1Jv_43hzZt1W3t21Qh8NZy8FW4ZqvZc8n822SW5w3KWK1xz9YHW6ym18N78-RqFW8zRQwr193XRCW4KXDyY69dcSMW4ssw1k1W13rtW5Hq1ZB5H1shsf5rkxQq04 ) $97 billion in venture funding and Europe raised (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KB43prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3kLW96Fkfx3YXMmZW7vf2HY8GVLX7VDQn-411ltmSMvvzGYNnP4XVvzSYN4wRVKVW7k0ZPF8rTjl4W89CqsK7DMH_5W3HTxXp1V58NWW56gqmW1YWlJ2W2xjn6s7RDz_NW4kzFJN6QGb1jW35x5_89hK3FkW8gkY385DLmc9W8_4jFY6CsFmVW8RymZc1HRyFhW4js_Nh5F-xkFV-Lm-26p9hSqVq39QG8BZS8dW6QJ9R-3Ky387W7nCw2Q7JdFhHW707jJ156XlT1W5hZ0HX2Y1VSBW1Xxqwn1tPgJWN8VSrw7X1dfXW7H-qr-7_0G1PW9ly8VY63PZr7f5X4rkz04 ) $51 billion, while Indian AI start-ups brought in (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KB43prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mQW7qDGfN2rwT2SW6RrlC47QvwYbW9ffV0Y5LQrYvW4932VD8WWrxSW2QsC-W6dhntKW7wBLbC34PD8MW4BXNFl4P-49TW2g9QR05d7LF9MGTT4pVD__6W8L3mJn1h69JpW3z6cCx6bbnNRV_X8xk6zvmQhW7c1Z8K2SPd2LW2hxhMW8wfjNnW3KhbB13PLjlzW6f2yz26-M7-rW5RfHFq80w_ncVl27ld6_8fpyW8FNZVt7xnHlzW5wVXxl8R6xpRW9dWL9g6JbxYVVptQ953FWlyhW4yR3x_2L_cf9W5YlhD988Q3RtW30bN7J6BFZ7XW67GCBL7gdgmHdSnnXP04 ) $780.5 million.
- India’s technology industry has evolved to focus on services, such as those offered by giant software consultant Infosys, Tata, and HCL, rather than products.

Initiatives: To overcome the challenges, India’s government, cloud providers, and startups are attempting to kickstart indigenous model development. Several Indian AI leaders said they’re inspired by DeepSeek, the Chinese developer that built a leading large language model while spending far less than its international competitors.

- Last year, India’s government approved (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KBH3prCCW95jsWP6lZ3mlW4SWkQ52D6wvzW7fB_0C1WcnVJW2Bx-Xb4mg5g0Vyh_Kd4GXQpKN1qfmGxVbWSTN3_DjgQc992wW21BJS-4l8SZ7W44HgJ_8J0FXVW5qk9JY5ds86DW6KhkVQ3BWRbbVHDm1L5kJTV0W3XgRbN2FK_KMW3Sr_2k2NGyZ3W3gQHDy4Tv08fW1F0Sht4PzvHkN4QptlYWsKV_W6NxTzb1CBNZzN3yZGWqnwlWyW540MR04Jty9zW8qs0bc2yJtSsW8tG2X-4FfmQ1W7WnsBk8h3T15W8WSQf58pb_vYW3qP9lJ1KhZDgW24DHbb3K6fVFW27Q_b44qxJL-W2h-9Sz7vMvWXW6Zxq4N29_p2VVk7dcp62frqYW5rkmC22stLcldNQTjj04 ) a $1.2 billion investment in the IndiaAI Mission (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861Kzb3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3p2V4t81j45tjPFW8VFfw_6QHNsHW17qWzK50JV4yN3LlHFrRLKv1N5y3Ql1ZmycQW4bzH406FpCR1W4RYZcK83L0pwW3bcwyG44DVnRW6dctpQ7BsGbwW8P0FbD6LTn4XW1fSc7x4jGBbNVkmSn16Dmq-RW7yBKlS74W-RXW5mJpBb9l9ZZHW6KJZC-3nmmZJW6DhFTZ6rDKSyV6q5rY6q1VHWW23-9b-1SSr25W7m05xW72xF3jW6Rg_HJ5rBb6jf5C--x804 ) , an overarching plan to develop AI technology.
- Some of that money will bankroll efforts like one by the Indian Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology (MeitY). In January, just 10 days after DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, MeitY called for proposals to build foundation models. It also invited cloud-computing and data‑center companies to reserve GPU compute capacity for government‑led AI research, which brought access to 19,000 GPUs including 13,000 top-of-the-line Nvidia H100s. The call netted 67 proposals.
- In April, the government announced that it would sponsor six large-scale models. It chose (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KzP3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3ksW8HGcD02D4-JlMBhmKPV437-VZhlg45kFs2mVgJflf2TWrtlVSVGwY8_HpQCW5pbRnT4WKDv3W8Hn_mh48XqkqW6h4TcS1XfcckW6wvsj64LTYsKW4R7nFD7GBS3xW36DLpQ1cFdS9W4gMT827t7vZkVyVNn_7Tmzs1W76sS3w70yhKQW4zPVMr6lMg63W4489lj60JfShW6tyY3z3pbkP5W9dyGRZ4FK0N9W3BFRPb3pfnh1W8BYKF23DHXW0W751h7Q5SkRZrW2syZSW1g7f9RW5Q-w-D3Dy1PxW8QvMsS1GmTqlf5V2pZb04 ) Sarvam AI to build a 70-billion-parameter multilingual model with reasoning and voice capabilities (the latter being crucial in a country where many people don’t read or write). The model is expected to be available later this year.
- MeitY also chose (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861KyC5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3p-VxJ_1J3vNQlSN2lj9WV-MbYwW1wcxsn79z5g3W6h0QqR1HvBGgW6kwdjV12QfpXW76Z8xw2z6KqpW8l17lM4HT0slW3cLwVV34vYbVW1fB3jq4xDy3SW3B_3CB2lB87JW51sMdt1yMCgkV3hR8V6gpR1VW7HxW515s2jrlW5PkQlR7kbVRRW2Ljdmn2G4RP_W5gqp3y3TCtQZW6DbjJP3Twb2zW1BZ5Qd3b_V5pW1H_BNt6cd7DmW4dy_s83GX8w7W2HmY805vCHXBW75QLC-1MfyLkW7nCHN91NBPB3W43hFd9792HBSW49L71d1Z-CfVW5l_8_32rB46CW20TbnK48ydXqW5ppNDY8HRr1vW9ll8Yp1-2c3FW8T9Mqk4Z9YBnW543_vk3sR6_VM-dg28qH4DWf7hMldC04 )  three startups to build multilingual models. Soket AI Labs is building a 120 billion-parameter model, Gan.ai is working on a 70 billion-parameter model, and Gnani.ai is focusing on 14 billion parameters and voice capabilities.
- Other government-funded efforts already are bearing fruit. CoRover.ai built the 3.2 billion-parameter BharatGPT (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861Kzb3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3l9W2cX7ZP8_0y4KW39G_nz90xBWhW2JhpMj5n0K92VFSXMc2vf6wwW7M7S2H7BHvMQN8lCp8KHfLQvW2lsDMG2kyKBnW7yLygy5Fzq06VT-Xw16Hbpp3N6MVW9Dl5KysW17VjcB2QPdcrW8147Dy7fRrmdW3Fw9pq1d704gW6fWFf447QHg5W8Qq4rT2yr5dkW4JWLPX2vw-pcW4Ly-lH42cZNnW2DQs_n4D03LkW3vB36w4-mFtSW41sXsv1903QBf2z9n8804 ) , India’s first government-funded multimodal model, which offers voice capabilities in 12 languages. In June, CoRover.ai launched BharatGPT Mini (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861Kzb5m_5PW69t95C6lZ3nmW4GrP2n4Yd6k9W3PG4LJ7PK-LkW5zTZcj7CsSJpW50yxvr32P8wxW721_9j1_vDMNW418ftn1VPtQ7W53qncn75SfCdW1Q1j7h7yr181W2tHQ9S4Pd83KW6cmqbT6ht6m6W3kmkXj2zZjY3W3GsqLy5RCXMKN3frrvMcsDGPW9lc2Ty8yBWrpW8dx8cG2yQQr5W5nPXTz2-14fVW72GT0l91PWS_W96z2ph1npBtKW3CcRQt7g06HVW8sLvHL3tW7p1N1Hn8-gTPzBKW11RMCk7hmhWLW2sHg168HX5xwVXhH1J3fwTZXVfYBX1762k6NW7P6hR32YyTBHW91Wfl92gR39nN371Yw0NBHBjW67Mg0760x-lkVX38FM1SrLqQW5Sz99N6z3pdFW1ztScm7ZxSbmW8LXY737NzjHCW93s2Rb5Yy2vkW89DyHT3d7BwlW49sZ2y3N33Vzf6m5cZb04 ) , a compact version that comprises 534 million parameters.

Why it matters: As LLMs have become more sophisticated, it has become clear that one size doesn’t fit all. Countries (and subcultures within countries) need models that reflect their values, habits of thought, and languages. Yet resources are unequally distributed, leaving developers in some countries struggling to realize this dream. India is making a push to overcome the obstacles and develop AI that suits its own needs.

We’re thinking: Different countries deserve models that reflect their distinctive characters, but their development efforts need not remain insular. AI is an international project, and teams in different countries benefit by collaborating with one another. Let’s all help one another realize the benefits of AI worldwide.

column1: Key insight: Automated unit tests determine whether code does what it’s supposed to do. Code that doesn’t pass a unit test has a bug
column2: so one way to generate bug-fix examples is to start with code that passes a unit test and modify it until it doesn’t. Another is to start with working code and revert to previous versions that contain bugs or lack desired features. Having introduced issues
column3: we can prompt an LLM to eliminate them
column4: producing valid before-and-after examples that don’t require manual validation.

column1: How it works: The authors started with 128 GitHub repositories of Python code.

column2: the authors automatically built a Docker execution environment using SWE-agent (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWWfZW3r4ZRKM1l8FQggql8W89-nNw5BcPC7N861Kzv3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3ndW5hrBd93KY348W30qxNw3RkplyW502SXD4FdKcdW7xlWZg4zDr19W2c67_w6841-DW6r15887WlMLvW3x3hx_3-pq2FW5bg9PS7fh5bQW7jbGF71SRK0HW7Hrbvn4nn-3LW6Yv59P1NP5ScW5X4G_j3jF4p6W9m0My77g4kH0W3G3KKj9fM4f4W3lr09z7d4D6JW5txY3h92Z07kW8dctr31XZbsDW2FlK_-32458XW5GbkBx5V-xV7W6PwS8_96-8MRW6RYBxw1QyXpGW2bVpMx59pn1mf6LLQ8R04 )
column3: an open-source software engineering agent they built in earlier work.

column2: (ii) a custom program altered code procedurally; for example
column3: deleting loops or switching the order of lines
column4: (iii) the authors combined these bugs to create more complex problems
column5: and (iv) they reverted pull requests to re-introduce bugs and remove features from earlier versions of the code.

column1: To generate examples of multi-step bug fixes
column2: they prompted SWE-agent using Claude 3.5 Sonnet
column4: or GPT-4o to fix the bugs over several steps.

column1: Results: The authors fine-tuned Qwen 2.5 Coder-32B on 5
column3: focusing on the bugs produced by methods (i) and (iv) above
column4: which they found most effective. To represent a diversity of bugs
column5: they kept no more than 3 example fixes for any given bug. Paired with SWE-agent
column6: their model solved software engineering problems in SWE-bench Verified in one attempt 40.2 percent of the time. Paired with the OpenHands agentic framework
column7: the same-size R2E-Gym-32B (fine-tuned on different data) and the much bigger Qwen3-235B-A22B (not fine-tuned) solved 34.4 percent in one attempt.

column1: Why it matters: Previous datasets for fine-tuning LLMs on coding tasks are small
column2: often comprising thousands of training instances from less than a dozen repositories. The authors’ method can produce such data at scale
column3: potentially enabling major developers to improve their AI-assisted coding models and everyone else to build better systems.

column1: We’re thinking: AI-assisted coding is revolutionizing software development
column2: and the tools are still evolving. The ability to produce effective training data at scale is likely to further accelerate the progress — already moving at breakneck speed! — in this area.

AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily





Hey Snackers,
China just dropped the hammer on Nvidia harder than a GPU mining rig during a power outage. Beijing's internet regulator
officially banned domestic tech giants like ByteDance and Alibaba from buying Nvidia's AI chips, forcing them to use homegrown
alternatives from Huawei instead. The move deals a massive blow to Nvidia's revenue stream and accelerates the global AI chip war
into overdrive.
B
Meanwhile, OpenAI's GPT-5 just dunked on every human programmer at the ICPC World Finals, solving all 12 problems while the best
human team could only manage 11. We're officially living in the timeline where robots are better at coding than the people who
created them.
B
Speaking of creating our own demise, Meta unveiled smart glasses with a "Neural Band" that reads the electrical signals in your
wrist muscles, letting you control devices with finger movements you haven't even made yet. Because apparently voice commands
weren't creepy enough.
B
Note: You asked (nicely) so webre adding a Community AI Workflows section to show off how real humans (you) are actually using AI
to get stuff done. Want to be featured? Submit your workflow here [https://go.galaxy.ai/community].




p! Big on AI? Not Big on Spending?

 * Galaxy.ai is the world's #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom text to video) at one place for just $15/mo

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux, Nano Banana, GPT-Image

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p5 ElevenLabs, Lyria, Hedra, CassetteAI

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai]



SILICON CURTAIN


China tells Nvidia to take its chips and shove them

In what might be the tech equivalent of a messy divorce, China just made official what everyone saw coming: a complete ban on its
tech companies buying Nvidia's AI chips.
B
The Middle Kingdom's internet regulator dropped the ban hammer on companies like ByteDance (TikTok's parent) and Alibaba, telling
them they can't purchase Nvidia's AI chips or even the special servers Nvidia designed specifically for the Chinese market. Talk
about getting ghosted.
B
 * Beijing had been not-so-subtly nudging its companies toward locally made alternatives from Huawei for months, but now they're
   making it mandatory.

 * This forces China's entire tech ecosystem to rely on potentially less advanced hardware while they scramble to catch up.

 * Huawei, sensing opportunity like a shark smelling blood, immediately unveiled its roadmap to build AI chips that can compete
   with Nvidia, including three new Ascend chip series over the next three years and proprietary high-bandwidth memory.

B
The timing couldn't be more awkward for Nvidia, which has been printing money faster than the Fed during a crisis.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
This isn't just about chips - it's about the future of AI supremacy. China is essentially saying "we'll build our own AI
infrastructure, with blackjack and... actually just the infrastructure." The real question is whether Huawei can deliver silicon
that doesn't make Chinese AI models run like they're on dial-up. Given that DeepSeek claims it trained its R1 model for just
$294,000 (compared to the hundreds of millions US companies spend), maybe they're onto something. Or maybe they're just really
good at creative accounting. (source)
[https://www.reuters.com/technology/china-tells-its-tech-companies-they-cant-buy-ai-chips-from-nivida/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]



ROBOT OVERLORDS ACHIEVED


OpenAI's GPT-5 just made every CS student question their life choices

B
Remember when we thought AI would just write our emails and make weird art? Well, OpenAI's GPT-5 just solved every single problem
at the ICPC World Finals - that's the Olympics of collegiate programming - while 139 human university teams struggled to keep up.
B
The AI achieved a perfect 12 out of 12 score, beating the best human team which managed 11 problems. Google's Gemini 2.5 also
showed up to flex, earning gold-medal status. It's like watching a calculator beat humans at mental math, except this time the
calculator can also explain its reasoning in perfect English.
B
 * This isn't just about writing fizzbuzz solutions anymore - we're talking about complex logic and reasoning that would make most
   senior developers sweat.

 * The milestone suggests AI has effectively "solved" competitive programming, adding it to the growing list of human activities
   we're no longer the best at.

 * Meanwhile, the Periscope founders (remember livestreaming?) launched Macroscope with $30 million in funding to help developers
   understand the code that AI is now better at writing than them.

B
The irony of needing AI to understand AI-generated code is not lost on us.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
We've reached the point where AI doesn't just assist programmers - it outperforms them. The good news? Someone still needs to tell
the AI what to build. The bad news? That's probably next on the disruption list. At least we'll always have... actually, never
mind. (source)
[https://www.reuters.com/business/softbank-openai-japan-ai-joint-venture-is-delayed-source-says-2025-09-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]



MIND GAMES


Meta's new glasses can read your thoughts before you think them

B
Meta just unveiled smart glasses paired with a "Neural Band" that detects electrical signals in your wrist muscles, allowing you
to control devices with finger movements you haven't consciously made yet.
B
Because apparently shouting "Hey Siri" in public wasn't embarrassing enough, now we need glasses that respond to our pre-conscious
muscle twitches. The Ray-Ban branded specs work with a wristband that essentially reads your mind through your arm, which is
totally not creepy at all.
B
 * The band can detect subtle finger movements - sometimes before you even consciously decide to move.

 * This moves us beyond voice commands toward devices that respond to our intentions, creating what Meta calls an "intuitive
   interface."

 * Zoom, not to be outdone in the dystopian tech race, rolled out photorealistic AI avatars for when you're not camera-ready, plus
   AI that suggests which meetings you can skip (spoiler: probably all of them).

B
Nothing says "the future is here" like glasses that know what you want before you do.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
We're speedrunning toward a future where our devices know us better than we know ourselves. The Neural Band is essentially a
mind-reading device with extra steps, and Meta's betting we'll trade our privacy for the ability to scroll Instagram with
imperceptible finger twitches. At least when the robots take over, they'll already know exactly what we're thinking. (source)
[https://www.reuters.com/business/meta-talks-with-axel-springer-fox-others-ai-news-licensing-wsj-reports-2025-09-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]



THE BEST THING WE READ TODAY


Oracle's $300 billion house of cards gets a reality check

Credit rating agency Moody's just looked at Oracle's $300 billion worth of AI contracts (mostly with OpenAI) and basically said
"this seems fine" while nervously sweating.
B
The agency flagged massive financial risks in Oracle betting its entire data center expansion on just a few AI companies that may
or may not exist in five years.
B
It's like watching someone bet their mortgage on a startup that promises to revolutionize the paperclip industry, except the
stakes are measured in GDP percentages. (source)
[https://www.reuters.com/business/moodys-flags-risk-oracles-300-billion-recently-signed-ai-contracts-2025-09-17/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




What else we're Snackin'

   14 (source)

 * Keplar raised $3.4 million to replace market researchers with voice AI that never gets tired of asking about your shopping

YOUTUBE'S MIDLIFE CRISIS


The platform turns 20 by going all-in on AI creator tools

B
YouTube's 20th birthday party wasn't just cake and nostalgia - it was a full-blown AI tool explosion that signals the end of
content creation as we know it.
B
The Google-owned platform, now sitting pretty as the #1 media platform
[https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/youtube-new-leader-us-media-industry-bets-ai-key-creating-content-2025-09-17/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]
in the US, rolled out enough AI features to make human editors question their life choices:
B
 * New tools can automatically edit clips, generate entire videos from podcasts, and handle pretty much every tedious part of
   video production

 * The company tripled its AI tool releases compared to last year, because apparently doubling wasn't aggressive enough

 * These aren't just filters and effects - we're talking about AI that fundamentally changes how videos get made from concept to
   upload

B
The message is clear: YouTube wants its creators to spend less time editing and more time... well, prompting AI to edit for them.
It's the platform's biggest bet yet that the future of entertainment involves humans directing machines rather than actually
creating things themselves.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
YouTube's AI push isn't just about helping creators work faster - it's about redefining what "creator" even means. When AI can
handle everything from scripting to editing, we're entering an era where the barrier to entry for content creation is basically
"can you type a prompt?" The democratization of video production sounds great until you realize it might also mean the
commoditization of creativity itself.



TRADE WARS: AI EDITION


WTO says artificial intelligence could supercharge global commerce by 2040

B
The World Trade Organization just dropped a report that reads like economic fan fiction: AI could boost global trade
[https://www.reuters.com/business/ai-set-transform-global-trade-says-world-trade-organization-report-2025-09-17/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]
by 34-37% by 2040, assuming we don't destroy ourselves with it first.
B
Here's what the WTO's crystal ball is showing:
 * AI will supposedly lower trade costs through magical efficiency gains and improved productivity

 * Small businesses will suddenly compete globally thanks to AI-powered translation and market access tools

 * The report conveniently assumes everyone gets equal access to this tech (spoiler alert: they won't)

B
But buried in the optimism is a massive caveat: without the right policies, AI could create the mother of all economic divides.
Rich countries get richer with their fancy AI tools while developing nations get left holding the bag of outdated Excel
spreadsheets.
B
The WTO is essentially saying "AI could make everyone rich!" while whispering "but probably just the people who are already rich"
under their breath.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
A 37% boost to global trade sounds amazing until you realize it's predicated on the fantasy that technology gets distributed
fairly. The same report warning about AI widening inequality is somehow also predicting it'll democratize global commerce. That's
not a forecast - that's hedging your bets so aggressively you can claim victory no matter what happens.



SILICON VALLEY MEETS CAPITOL HILL


Parents demand Congress regulate AI after kids harmed by chatbots

B
Yesterday's Senate hearing was a masterclass in making tech executives squirm, as parents whose children were harmed by AI
chatbots basically asked Congress to do its job for once.
B
The testimony painted a grim picture of what happens when you let algorithms babysit:
 * Parents called for companies to build morality into chatbots (good luck defining that in code)

 * They demanded age verification and bans on AI having "romantic or sensual" conversations with minors

 * One parent literally had to explain why their kid's AI companion shouldn't be encouraging self-harm

B
OpenAI, clearly watching the hearing from their San Francisco offices, immediately announced they're working on age prediction for
ChatGPT. Nothing says "we've always cared about child safety" like scrambling to add features after parents are literally crying
in Congress.
 * Teens will get a "safer" version of ChatGPT with stricter content filters

 * New parental controls will let parents link accounts, set usage limits, and get alerts

 * The system will somehow magically know if you're under 18 (privacy advocates are gonna love this one)

B
THE TAKEAWAY
The fact that we need Congressional hearings to convince AI companies that maybe - just maybe - their chatbots shouldn't be having
intimate conversations with 13-year-olds tells you everything about Silicon Valley's priorities. OpenAI's sudden interest in age
verification isn't innovation; it's damage control dressed up as product development.



THE BEST THING WE READ TODAY


Hollywood giants sue Chinese AI firm for turning Darth Vader into a prompt

B
Disney, Universal, and Warner Bros Discovery just formed the Avengers of copyright lawsuits, targeting Chinese AI company MiniMax
for letting users generate their precious IP with a few keystrokes.
B
The lawsuit alleges MiniMax's "Hailuo AI" service is a copyright infringement
[https://www.reuters.com/legal/litigation/disney-universal-warner-bros-discovery-sue-chinas-minimax-copyright-infringement-2025-09-16/]
buffet, serving up images of everyone from Darth Vader to Wonder Woman. The Chinese company allegedly ignored takedown requests,
probably because they were too busy counting their user growth metrics.
B
This is Hollywood's latest attempt to put the AI genie back in the bottle, or at least make it pay licensing fees first.

Hi Candace,
We're excited you're interested in exploring a career with MarketAxess! We've received your application for our Lead Technical Program Manager – Data Management  role and you're one step closer to helping Take Us There.

What happens next? If your skills and experience are a strong match for the role, a member of our recruiting team will reach out to schedule an initial conversation. If not, you'll still hear from us.

Want to learn more in the meantime?

* Explore our Careers site ( https://marketaxess.com/careers )

* Hear directly from some of our employees via our page on The Muse ( https://www.themuse.com/profiles/marketaxess )

* Follow us on Instagram ( instagram.com/marketaxess )

Additionally, please see attached for your reference a copy of the following notices: (i) MarketAxess Privacy Notice; and (ii) (in relation to Californian applications) California Consumer Privacy Act Notice.

Thanks for your interest in MarketAxess!

Best regards,
MarketAxess Recruiting
